---
<BaseLayout
  title="About | Supplement Shop Singapore"
  description="Non-commercial buying literacy for supplement shopping in Singapore."
  path="/about/"
  image="/japan-perspective-infographic.png"
>
  <script slot="head" type="application/ld+json" set:html={orgJsonLd}></script>

  <h1>Purpose</h1>

  <p>
    This site exists to give Singapore residents a structured, non-commercial starting point for supplement purchasing decisions. The focus is buying literacy — not product promotion.
  </p>

  <h2>What This Site Does Not Do</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>No product sales or affiliate links</li>
    <li>No product rankings, comparisons, or recommendations</li>
    <li>No dosage guidance of any kind</li>
    <li>No medical, treatment, or health outcome claims</li>
    <li>No urgency or scarcity marketing</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Approach</h2>
  <p>
    Content is written for a Singapore audience and shaped in part by how steady, long-term supplement habits are discussed in Japan. The goal is to improve label reading, seller evaluation, and purchase decision quality — not to influence which product someone chooses.
  </p>
  <p>
    This site covers the practical side of supplement shopping in Singapore: channel differences, label terminology, seller verification, and common purchase traps.
  </p>

  <figure class="infographic">
    <img
      src="/japan-perspective-infographic.png"
      alt="A Japan Perspective: Consistency Over Quick Fixes — infographic showing three core principles: consistent timing, stable intake, and periodic review, with a comparison of quick-fix versus long-term mindsets."
      width="1024"
      height="571"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <figcaption>
      Cultural reference only. This is not medical advice — discuss your supplement routine with a qualified clinician.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Regulatory Context: Health Sciences Authority (HSA) Singapore</h2>
  <p>
    Health supplements sold in Singapore fall under the oversight of the <strong>Health Sciences Authority (HSA)</strong>, the national regulatory agency responsible for health products under the <em>Health Products Act (Cap. 122D)</em>. The HSA regulates the safety, quality, and labelling of health supplements through its Health Products Regulation Group.
  </p>
  <p>
    Under this framework, health supplements are classified as a subset of health products. Sellers and importers are responsible for ensuring their products meet applicable standards before placing them on the Singapore market. The HSA maintains a consumer advisory portal (HSAsg) where buyers can check for product alerts, safety notices, and recall information.
  </p>
  <p>
    Key points of the oversight framework relevant to Singapore supplement shoppers:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Labelling requirements:</strong> Products must carry accurate ingredient lists, serving sizes, and manufacturer details in line with HSA guidelines.</li>
    <li><strong>Prohibited substances:</strong> The HSA publishes lists of prohibited and controlled ingredients; products containing them may be subject to enforcement action.</li>
    <li><strong>No pre-market approval for most supplements:</strong> Unlike medicines, most health supplements do not require individual pre-market approval from HSA. Responsibility for compliance sits with the importer or distributor.</li>
    <li><strong>Consumer alerts:</strong> The HSA issues consumer alerts for adulterated, counterfeit, or mislabelled supplement products. Checking these alerts before purchasing is a practical step.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This regulatory context does not remove the need for individual label evaluation. Understanding the HSA framework helps shoppers interpret what regulatory status does — and does not — guarantee about any given product.
  </p>

  <h2>Related Resources</h2>
  <p>
    For a broader overview of the supplement landscape in Singapore, visit the <a href="https://supplementsingapore.neoi.jp">Supplements Singapore guide</a>.
  </p>

